  "market_context": "ES had just taken out the previous day low, sweeping sellside liquidity. On the upside, a swing high with a lower swing high to its right formed failure swings, providing buy-side liquidity as a draw for the anticipated rally.",
  "key_observation": "After sweeping the previous day low, a down-close candle was closed through, validating a bullish order block. Its mean threshold held, a propulsion block formed off it, and successive mean thresholds were respected through the rally to the failure-swing highs.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Identify that price just swept the previous day low, taking sellside liquidity.",
    "Mark the failure swing highs above (swing high with lower swing high to the right) as the buy-side liquidity draw.",
    "Wait for a reaction off the swept low and a closure over the series of down-close candles to validate the first bullish order block.",
    "Note the order block sits in premium relative to the immediate swing, so use the mean threshold for entry or wait for a second entry.",
    "Observe the mean threshold holding, then a second order block forming with its own mean threshold marked.",
    "Confirm the diagram-like setup: sweep of the low + failure swings above + down-close candle into the level + closure validates the order block.",
    "Take entry at the order block with stop below the high resistance liquidity (swept low) and target the failure swing highs.",
    "Note that as price closes over the down-close candles, a propulsion block forms whose mean threshold is continuously respected.",
    "Explain why the un-swept low is not trusted for invalidation — without a sweep there is no high resistance liquidity, so wait for the sweep before relying on it.",
    "Once that low is swept, another order block forms off the propulsion block and its mean threshold holds, allowing continuation higher."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade ran higher to take profit at the failure swing highs; multiple subsequent order blocks and propulsion blocks held their mean thresholds as price continued up.",
  "lessons": "Order blocks are validated by a closure through opposing candles after a liquidity sweep; mean threshold provides a tighter entry, and propulsion blocks built off prior order blocks should respect their mean thresholds. Use high resistance liquidity (swept lows) for invalidation, not un-swept lows.",
